	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New convention could turn the tide for the PNG tuna industry</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> Experts from the Pacific region, the Papua New Guinea (PNG) government and non-government stakeholders from the fisheries sector met in June and July 2004 to help to implement the new Convention on the Conservation and Management of Highly Migratory Fish Stocks in the Western and Central Pacific Ocean that entered into force in June 2004. PNG?s draft tuna fishery management plan is being developed in line with this new Convention.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> This plan will maintain a total allowable catch (TAC) limit for the mid-water and surface tuna fishery with the maximum catch for yellowfin and big-eye tuna in mid-water set at 10,000 tonnes per year. For the more than 200 tuna purse-seiners fishery, the TAC would be 338,000 tonnes per annum, inclusive of the catch of skipjack, yellowfin and big-eye tunas.</p><p> The policy states that in allocating licenses, preference will be given by the National Fisheries Authority (NFA) to national fishing companies using PNG registered and flagged vessels. This is designed to encourage local on-shore processing operations.</p><p>
 According to the NFA, PNG?s rapidly growing tuna-export industry could enjoy a yearly turnover of US$1 billion (K3 billion) if most of the catch is processed locally. Currently 94% of the tuna caught in PNG waters is shipped to Thailand, the Philippines and other countries without coming ashore. With greater local investment, the NFA hold that it would be more attractive for fishing companies to land in PNG. &quot;The total annual catch is about 330,000 tonnes a year and we are trying to bring most of this onshore?, say NFA sources. They add that as a result of full EU recognition for the quality of NFA's audit and certification unit, new markets have been opened up, including in the United Kingdom. Since October 2002 PNG has been elevated to &quot;list &quot;1or EU fishery imports.<br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Pacific Islands Development Program, Pacific islands reports, 
<a href="http://archives.pireport.org/archive/2004/july/07%2D20%2D16.htm" target="_self">July</a> and 
<a href="http://pidp.eastwestcenter.org/pireport/2004/August/08-04-18.htm" target="_self">August</a> 2004</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thenational.com.pg/0809/business1.htm" target="_self">The National &quot;press article, August 2004</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/development/body/csp_rsp/print/pg_csp_en.pdf" target="_self">Papua New Guinea &quot;European Community Country Strategy Paper and Nat...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.greenpeace.org.au/oceans/index.html" target="_self">Greenpeace reports on Pacific tuna fishing, 2004</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> PNG has jurisdiction over about one-fifth of the entire tuna stocks in the Pacific tuna fishery. However, these are underexploited by PNG and contribute only 1% to GDP. PNG has one of the richest fishing grounds left in the world, and more than 10,000 people are employed in commercial fishing with 30,000 coastal households depending on small-scale fisheries for their livelihood. Therefore it is vital to develop strategies that both address the sustainable exploitation of tuna resources and the improvement of local value-adding processing operations.</p><p> The example of PNG shows how regional co-operation between Pacific island nations that are signatories of the new Tuna Convention in the Western and Central Pacific Ocean, could enable economic and social benefits to accrue to island states.</p><p> Developing new strategies for the tuna fishery is also very timely given the potential evolution of their relations with the EU, and given the EUâ€™s growing interest and presence in the Pacific tuna fishery. As well as pursuing a strategy of signing bilateral agreements with Pacific island states, the EU is also a recent signatory to the new Pacific Tuna Convention. The PNG-EU Country Strategy Paper and National Indicative Programme for the period 2002 ? 2007, states that: &quot;In fisheries, the EC will ensure coherence between its commercial interests in harvesting tuna from the Pacific, and the developmental imperatives of equitable returns, promotion of on-shore fish processing and coastal fisheries, transparency in providing accurate information on fishing effort and catch, and strict adherence to the principles of resource conservation and sustainability?. This is very much in line with the NFA?s strategy for local investment and local landings. The fact that PNG is now on &quot;list &quot;1or exporting fishery products to the EU market is certainly another positive sign for the development of EU-PNG fishery relations.</p><p> However, it remains to be seen how effectively such strategies for sustainable development will be implemented at local and regional level in the mid- to long-term. In the past, pressure from the purse-seine sector has pushed Pacific islands to deliver more fishing licences than desirable for sustainable harvesting of the resources. Licence fees from distant-water fishing nations do provide much needed income for Pacific island governments, but there is an urgent need for better control and transparency on the licence-allocation systems from all Pacific states.</p><p> ?Money in the bank for the government now, or fish in the sea for the future and the development of our peopl &quot;es a dilemma facing many fishery-resource dependent ACP countries. It is a dilemma, which unless resolved, threatens to jeopardise efforts to develop local fisheries sectors in a sustainable and locally beneficial way. As was stated in a recent Greenpeace report on tuna fishing in the Pacific: &quot;We are only as strong as our weakest link?.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
